sec.p:
While the city-lament demonstrates the closest comparison with the poems on Lamentations, the differences show that ancient Israel felt free enough to reshape this particular genre in order to bring it into conformity with Israel’s experience. The narrator decries the destruction of the once-glorious city:


The LORD determined to lay in ruins

  the wall of daughter Zion;

he stretched the line;

  he did not withhold his hand from destroying;

he caused rampart and wall to lament;

  they languish together. (2:8)
